  "local_port": 32876,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What does an IFS officer do?",
  "response": "An Indian Foreign Service (IFS) officer is part of the diplomatic corps of India and is tasked with representing India in international affairs. Below are the primary responsibilities and duties of an IFS officer:\n\n1. **Diplomacy and Representation**:\n   - Promote and protect India's national interests abroad.\n   - Represent India in bilateral and multilateral fora.\n   - Foster and maintain diplomatic relations with other countries.\n\n2. **Negotiation**:\n   - Engage in negotiations on behalf of India concerning various international issues such as trade, peace, security, and cultural exchanges.\n\n3. **Policy Formulation**:\n   - Participate in the formulation and implementation of foreign policy.\n   - Provide policy recommendations to the Government of India.\n\n4. **Consular Services**:\n   - Provide consular support to Indian citizens abroad, including assistance in emergencies, legal aid, and issuance of travel documents like visas and passports.\n\n5. **Cultural Diplomacy**:\n   - Promote Indian culture, heritage, and values overseas through cultural programs and exchanges.\n   - Strengthen people-to-people bonds between India and other countries.\n\n6. **Information and Public Diplomacy**:\n   - Disseminate information regarding India through various media channels.\n   - Enhance India's image and foster goodwill through public diplomacy initiatives.\n\n7. **Economic Diplomacy**:\n   - Engage in economic and commercial diplomacy to encourage trade, investment, and economic cooperation.\n   - Support Indian businesses in navigating foreign markets and regulatory frameworks.\n\n8. **Multilateral Diplomacy**:\n   - Represent India in international organizations such as the United Nations, World Trade Organization, and other such fora.\n   - Advocate for India's positions on various global issues.\n\n9. **Administrative Roles**:\n   - Administrative duties within the Ministry of External Affairs when posted domestically.\n   - Handle human resources, budget, and other logistical aspects in Indian missions abroad.\n\n10. **Reporting**:\n    - Collect, analyze, and report on political, economic, and social developments in host countries.\n    - Prepare briefs and reports for the Indian government on various international matters.\n\nIFS officers are posted in Indian embassies, consulates, high commissions, and in the Ministry of External Affairs in India. Their career typically involves successive postings in different countries and different roles.",
